        marks: 6, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `• A floating-point number is stored as two parts: a signed fractional mantissa and a signed integer exponent. The represented value is mantissa × 2^exponent.\n• In a two\'s-complement representation, normalisation means: for a positive number the mantissa starts 0.1...; for a negative number it starts 1.0.... This ensures there are no wasted leading zeros or ones that carry no information.\n• Normalisation maximises precision because every bit of the mantissa after the sign bit holds a significant binary digit; unnormalised forms waste mantissa bits on leading redundancy.\n• Example: 0.001101 × 2^5 is unnormalised; shifting the point gives 0.1101 × 2^3 — same value, two extra bits of precision available in the mantissa.\n• Trade-off: the range is determined by the exponent width; extreme values may cause underflow/overflow, and values that cannot be represented exactly produce rounding errors.`
